From: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
Date: Sun, 05 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: ethernet: qualcomm: ppe: add a seam for tunnel flow offload

Dispatch flowtable rules carrying tunnel (ENC_*) match keys, which a
route through a VXLAN or GENEVE device produces, to a dedicated
handler. The handler declines them for now, keeping them on the
software path, and gates on the variant tunnel-engine flag so a
generation without the engine (HPPE) rejects them outright. It also
marks where a tunnel implementation slots in: the SoC has an on-die
tunnel engine - the tunnel lookup block, whose PPPoE session table is
already in use, and the tunnel fields of the egress L3 interfaces -
which can terminate and generate these encapsulations without an
external accelerator. IPsec stays out of scope either way, it runs on
the separate EIP-197 crypto engine with its own firmware.

Behavior is unchanged: such rules were already rejected by the match
key whitelist.

Signed-off-by: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/ppe_flowtable.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/qualcomm/ppe/ppe_flowtable.c
@@ -535,6 +535,38 @@ static void ppe_ft_vlan_put(struct ppe_f
 	ppe_fdb_vsi_flush(ft->ppe_dev, ppe_ft_vlan_vsi(index));
 }
 
+/* The match keys of a flow whose route terminates in a tunnel device
+ * (the tunnel parameters of a VXLAN or GENEVE destination).
+ */
+#define PPE_FT_TUNNEL_KEYS	(BIT_ULL(FLOW_DISSECTOR_KEY_ENC_CONTROL) | \
+				 BIT_ULL(FLOW_DISSECTOR_KEY_ENC_KEYID) | \
+				 BIT_ULL(FLOW_DISSECTOR_KEY_ENC_IPV4_ADDRS) | \
+				 BIT_ULL(FLOW_DISSECTOR_KEY_ENC_IPV6_ADDRS))
+
+/* Tunneled flows stay on the software path for now. The SoC carries a
+ * tunnel engine that could take them: the tunnel lookup block (which
+ * already hosts the PPPoE session table) terminates encapsulations
+ * into tunnel L3 interfaces, and the tunnel fields of the egress L3
+ * interfaces generate them. Driving it means programming the tunnel
+ * decap and encap header tables from the ENC keys of the rule pair,
+ * analogous to what the PPPoE session slots do.
+ */
+static int ppe_ft_tunnel_replace(struct ppe_flowtable *ft,
+				 struct flow_cls_offload *f)
+{
+	/* Tunnelled flows can only be offloaded on generations with the
+	 * on-die tunnel engine (APPE); elsewhere they stay on the
+	 * software path. Driving the engine (programming the decap and
+	 * encap header tables from the ENC keys, as the PPPoE slots do)
+	 * is not yet implemented, so the flow is declined for now even
+	 * where the engine exists.
+	 */
+	if (!ft->ppe_dev->variant->has_tunnel_engine)
+		return -EOPNOTSUPP;
+
+	return -EOPNOTSUPP;	/* TODO: program the tunnel engine */
+}
+
 /* Hash key of a flow's destination IP for the host refcount table. */
 static u32 ppe_ft_host_key(const struct ppe_flow_entry *flow)
 {
@@ -648,13 +680,15 @@ static int ppe_ft_flow_replace(struct pp
 	    !flow_rule_match_key(rule, FLOW_DISSECTOR_KEY_IPV6_ADDRS))
 		return -EOPNOTSUPP;
 
+	if (rule->match.dissector->used_keys & PPE_FT_TUNNEL_KEYS)
+		return ppe_ft_tunnel_replace(ft, f);
+
 	/* Match keys outside the supported set must reject the rule,
-	 * not be skipped: a tunnel route, for example, arrives as
-	 * ENC_* keys, which offloaded as a plain routed flow would
-	 * transmit the packets unencapsulated. The TCP flags key is a knowing
-	 * exception: the hardware forwards FIN/RST packets instead of
-	 * punting them, which only delays the flow teardown until the
-	 * flow idles out.
+	 * not be skipped: offloading a partially matched rule as a
+	 * plain routed flow would misforward the packets. The TCP
+	 * flags key is a knowing exception: the hardware forwards
+	 * FIN/RST packets instead of punting them, which only delays
+	 * the flow teardown until the flow idles out.
 	 */
 	if (rule->match.dissector->used_keys &
 	    ~(BIT_ULL(FLOW_DISSECTOR_KEY_META) |
